text: [Music]
my name is Sarah Mitchell I work as a
Solutions Architect in the financial
services team I've been at AWS for a
year so my job involves going to
customers in in banking and finance
sector and talking to them about how
they would build and deploy solutions on
the AWS platform the thing I find most
satisfying about being here is is just
the breadth of experience that you have
so not only do you have to see lots of
customers and they all have a different
set of problems and use cases but we
also have a really broad range of
technologies to apply to those problems
no two days are the same
you get you know sometimes you're out
and about sometimes you're back in the
office you know trying to work something
through or design a solution so outside
of the sort of normal day to day work
talking to customers there are all sorts
of opportunities to do things so writing
blogs and articles and educational
pieces I seem to have done a lot of
presenting and summit events I've
recorded things on YouTube so those
those things I wasn't used to doing and
I've spent quite a lot of time doing
that in the last year preparing for the
AWS interview is is something everyone
approaches differently I spent some time
thinking back over key projects that I
had worked on and I knew that the
questions would be around the AWS
leadership principles so it was a case
of trying to kind of sift through
previous projects previous jobs that
I've had and trying to extract how those
would apply to the leadership principles
AWS has such a broad range of technology
that it was an opportunity for me to
kind of diversify some of my skills I'm
spending a lot of time looking at data
and analytics machine learning which is
something I didn't have opportunity to
do elsewhere I've learned loads about
technology about Amazon about clouds
and the opportunity to sort of see those
things and be involved in how they work
is is fairly unique in the industry
[Music]
